snippet.textDisplay:
Long paragraphs ahead only read if you like physics and sports science:

I know this is just a movie, but if it is suggesting that sonic is running with forefoot strike for speed then it is more than likely true.

Marathon runners don't use it as much (only during the final burst at the end of a race) but sprinters use forefoot strike EXCLUSIVELY and sonic is more of a sprinter with supreme endurance.

When you are sprinting to reach top speed your legs are like pistons that try to apply as much linear force as possible and naturally a great amount of contact time with the ground is needed. Once at topspeed though you are trying to brush the ground as lightly as possible to maintain that top speed with minimal loss so you want minimal contact time with the ground.

This is why it's better to use forefoot strike because it decreases contact time as opposed to having your contact with the ground go from the heel all the way to the forefoot which would take considerable longer.

Think of it like spinning the wheel of the bike as fast as possible with your hands. At first you really make as much contact with it apply a lot of force but once at top speed(or max angular velocity) if you keep trying to apply more force with the same contact time you will only slow it down. It's a similar situation with sprinting.

I just thought of this but I have been watching some cheetah and greyhound videos and I have noticed how they keep their body level at all times when sprinting, minimising energy loss. Forefoot strike would be condusive to this in humans. Heel to toe strike would make you bounce up and down a lot as you see with a lot of joggers and would have energy leaks all over. You might be asking if heel strike has so much energy leakage then why don't marathon runners use it to prevent energy leaks too? I think that may be because forefoot strike is very exhausting itself. It is meant to reduce contact time but that means to apply the same amount of force to propel yourself requires greater frequency of stride and this may be a less efficient way to run for hours on end. So it's a necessary trade off.

But it's just a theory... A FILM THEORY.

snippet.textDisplay: as a cross country runner, i would like to make it clear that coaches push athletes to run on the ball of your foot, not the toes. Also heel striking is an incorrect way of running only because it can lead to many long term injuries. If you watch any competitive distance event, you will see that they land on the ball of their foot(which is under the big toe) and rolling towards the toe.
